node.text:
We know Mars had active volcanoes, including the solar system’s largest, Olympus Mons. But now, scientists have confirmed that one region experienced thousands of “super eruptions” over 500 million years.

A super eruption can blast the equivalent of 400 million Olympic-size swimming pools of molten rock and gas through the surface and spread a thick blanket of ash up to thousands of miles from the eruption site. Afterwards, a volcano of this magnitude collapses into a giant hole called a “caldera.” Seven calderas in Arabia Terra in northern Mars were the first giveaways that the region may once have hosted volcanoes capable of super eruptions. 

By studying the topography and mineral composition of Arabia Terra, scientists recently found evidence for thousands of such eruptions. They estimated that about 4 billions years ago they tore through the Martian surface for about 500 million years.
 
“Each one of these eruptions would have had a significant climate impact — maybe the released gas made the atmosphere thicker or blocked the Sun and made the atmosphere colder,” said Patrick Whelley, a geologist at NASA’s Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Maryland, who led the Arabia Terra analysis. “Modelers of the Martian climate will have some work to do to try to understand the impact of the volcanoes.”

In this artist’s rendition, we explore a metal-rich asteroid named Psyche, which offers a unique window into the building blocks of planet formation.

The NASA Psyche mission launches in 2022 and will arrive at the asteroid, which orbits the Sun between Mars and Jupiter, in 2026. The spacecraft, also named Psyche, will spend 21 months orbiting the asteroid, mapping it and studying its properties.

Join the mission at nasa.gov/psyche and http://psyche.asu.edu.

Set a course for Ganymede: on June 7, our Juno mission flew closer to Jupiter’s giant, icy moon than any spacecraft in more than two decades, then made its 34th flyby of Jupiter itself. For a “starship captain” point of view, enjoy this animation.

To create the video, actual JunoCam images were projected onto a digital sphere. Synthetic frames were added to provide views of approach and departure for both Ganymede and Jupiter.

Animation: Koji Kuramura, Gerald Eichstädt, Mike Stetson
Music: Vangelis 
Producer: Scott J. Bolton
Credit: NASA/JPL-Caltech/SwRI/MSSS

See more details at missionjuno.swri.edu and www.youtube.com/watch?v=CC7OJ7gFLvE

#NASA #space #science #nature #Jupiter #Ganymede #planets #JunoMission

node.text:
What would you say to people of the future?
 
After our #LucyMission completes its task of visiting 8 different asteroids, the spacecraft will continue to travel between the orbit of Jupiter and the orbit of the Earth for at least hundreds of thousands, if not millions of years. The Lucy team installed a plaque with messages of wisdom, joy, and inspiration from current poets and thought leaders for our descendants who may find the spacecraft floating among the planets.
 
Lucy will launch this fall on a 12-year journey to study 8 different asteroids.

Bennu is one of Earth’s closest planetary neighbors – an asteroid roughly the height of a skyscraper, and since late 2018, the place that NASA’s OSIRIS-REx mission has called home. When OSIRIS-REx arrived on December 3, 2018, it began wrapping Bennu in a complex web of observations. OSIRIS-REx departed Bennu on May 10, 2021 on a return voyage to Earth, bringing with it over 60 grams of sample collected from the asteroid. This narrated video presents the mission’s complete trajectory during its time at Bennu.

node.text:
We know Mars had active volcanoes, including the solar system’s largest, Olympus Mons. But now, scientists have confirmed that one region experienced thousands of “super eruptions” over 500 million years.

A super eruption can blast the equivalent of 400 million Olympic-size swimming pools of molten rock and gas through the surface and spread a thick blanket of ash up to thousands of miles from the eruption site. Afterwards, a volcano of this magnitude collapses into a giant hole called a “caldera.” Seven calderas in Arabia Terra in northern Mars were the first giveaways that the region may once have hosted volcanoes capable of super eruptions. 

By studying the topography and mineral composition of Arabia Terra, scientists recently found evidence for thousands of such eruptions. They estimated that about 4 billions years ago they tore through the Martian surface for about 500 million years.
 
“Each one of these eruptions would have had a significant climate impact — maybe the released gas made the atmosphere thicker or blocked the Sun and made the atmosphere colder,” said Patrick Whelley, a geologist at NASA’s Goddard Space Flight Center in Greenbelt, Maryland, who led the Arabia Terra analysis. “Modelers of the Martian climate will have some work to do to try to understand the impact of the volcanoes.”

The ultimate glow up ✨🌎

If you were looking down at Earth from the International Space Station, you would notice that our planet is surrounded by a faint, multicolored glow. This airglow is constantly shining at the boundary where Earth meets space. Airglow is produced when the atoms and molecules in our upper atmosphere interact with sunlight. 

Ethereal beauty aside, airglow is very useful to atmospheric scientists, helping them understand the upper atmosphere’s temperature, density, and composition, and trace how particles move through the region itself. 

This video, shot from the International Space Station in March 2012, shows airglow over the Middle East at night. 

Video credit: NASA

In this artist’s rendition, we explore a metal-rich asteroid named Psyche, which offers a unique window into the building blocks of planet formation.

The NASA Psyche mission launches in 2022 and will arrive at the asteroid, which orbits the Sun between Mars and Jupiter, in 2026. The spacecraft, also named Psyche, will spend 21 months orbiting the asteroid, mapping it and studying its properties.

Join the mission at nasa.gov/psyche and http://psyche.asu.edu.

#NASA #space #science #asteroids #Psyche #MissionToPsyche

node.text:
Reaching into space…and into the future. 📡〰️🛰

The giant antennas of NASA’s Deep Space Network are what makes it possible to track and communicate with the dozens of spacecraft exploring the solar system, from the Sun to out past Pluto.

Now, the global network is getting an upgrade.

See the details, take a 360-degree tour of one of the network's largest dishes, and see which missions are in contact with which ground stations right now, all at the link in our bio.

#NASA #space #science #engineering #DSN

🪐 Forty years ago today, Voyager 2 encountered Saturn. It revealed the wonders of the planet's moons and rings, and set the stage for the epic Cassini mission that followed.

At the temporary link in our bio, you can learn more, and hear Voyager and Cassini scientist Dr. Linda Spilker describe what it was like as the team met surprises – both good and bad – when Voyager 2 closed in on the planet.

We’re going back to Saturn with the Dragonfly mission, which will send a rotorcraft to fly from point to point on the ringed planet’s largest moon, Titan: nasa.gov/dragonfly

1. Saturn as seen by Voyager 2 in 1981.
2. Saturn's giant, enshrouded moon Titan.
3. A false-color view of Saturn.
4. A render of the Dragonfly spacecraft, which will explore Titan.

Check out that Venus-shine! 💡

On Aug. 9, @EuropeanSpaceAgency & @NASA’s Solar Orbiter flew by Venus, passing within 5,000 miles (about 8000 kilometers) of the planet’s surface. As it approached, the Solar Orbiter Heliospheric Imager telescope onboard — specializing in wide-field views — caught this gleaming view of Earth’s closest neighbor. 

The images show Venus on the left while the Sun is off camera to the upper right. The planet's nightside, the part hidden from the Sun, appears as a dark semicircle surrounded by a bright crescent of light – glare from Venus’ incredibly bright sunlit side.

Read more at nasa.gov/solarorbiter
